287","1419":"1419","um 1315":"about 1315","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cumbria, England, United Kingdom":"Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kirkbride","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English (Cumbria): habitational name from a place in Cumbria near Carlisle, named from Old Norse <i>kirkja</i> ‘church’ + the Irish saint's name <i>Bride</i> (see   Kilbride  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilbride","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Kieran, Aidan.","Irish (Connacht) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Brighde</b> (Irish) or <b>Mac Gille Brighde</b> (Scottish) ‘son of the servant of (Saint) Brigit’, also often shortened and Anglicized as   McBride  . The name <i>Brigit</i> means ‘exalted’. Brigit was originally a pagan goddess, many of whose attributes, such as a sacred fire, became attached to the historical figure of Saint Brigit of Kildare (452–523), founder of the first Irish convent.","Scottish: habitational name from any of various places with this name, from Gaelic <i>Cill Bríghde</i> ‘church of Saint Brigit’ (<i>cill</i> being from Latin <i>cella</i> ‘room, cell’), for example Kilbride in Lanarkshire."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":67,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Kirkbride was born about 1315, in England, her father, Walter de Kirkbride, was 30 and her mother, Alice De Bourdon, was 36. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas L'Engleys."},"et":{"um 1315–":"umbes 1315–Surnud","1314–1349":"1314–1349","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1355–1419":"1355–1419","1305–1420":"1305–1420","1287–1336":"1287–1336","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud",